### Describe the feature you'd like to request

Currently, using

```json
experimental: {
  outputStandalone: true
}
```

in a `next.config.json` will produce a `server.js` file that will encode the environment variables into the bundle at build-time. 

Currently our `next.config.js` looks like this;

```javascript
module.exports = {
  serverRuntimeConfig: {
    someSecret: process.env.SOME_SECRET,
  },
  publicRuntimeConfig: {
    someValue: process.env.SOME_VALUE,
  }
}
```

and once we have done a `next build` with the standalone experimental bundler, we end up with `server.js` looking something like;

```javascript
// ...
"serverRuntimeConfig": { someSecret: 'test' },
"publicRuntimeConfig": { someValue: '' },
// ...
```

Where it has resolved the `process.env.*` at build-time.

This - although it works - is less than desirable for our use case as we like having control of these variables at runtime when running our Docker image in k8s.

### Describe the solution you'd like

Ideally a way to tell Next.js to _not_ encode/bundle these values at build time, and instead leave them unchanged.

Ideally, I want the `server.js` to remain as;

```javascript
// ...
"serverRuntimeConfig": { someSecret: process.env.SOME_SECRET },
"publicRuntimeConfig": { someValue: process.env.SOME_VALUE },
// ...
```

As this then allows us to inject these `process.env.*` values at runtime, having more control over the application.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Currently I've experimented with automatically re-writing the `server.js` file once it gets built, and replacing with our pre-defined serverRuntime & publicRuntime config objects. This works perfectly - and is currently running perfectly well in our experimental k8s cluster/deployment pipeline :)

