When you use a middleware on the root route (so, directly in the `pages` folder), it also kicks in for other kind of requests like API calls or static assets (like `favicon.ico`).
When one uses middleware for page routes (not API routes), I always thought that the middleware is only executed for requests for pages, but ignores "the rest". But this is not the case.

Example to reproduce:

1. Create new app: `npx create-next-app@12.1.0 --use-npm --ts root-middleware`
2. Add a middleware file that `console.log`s the route's base path:
```tsx
export default async function _middlewareIndex(req: NextRequest) {
  // /some-route/abc/123
  const pathname = req.nextUrl.pathname;
  // /some-route
  const basePath = `/${pathname.split("/")[1]}`;

  console.log("Middleware: ", basePath)

  return NextResponse.next();
}
```
3. Run the app `npm run dev` and visit `http://localhost:3000/`
4. Look at your (server) console, it will show that the middleware not only intercepted for the page request (`/`), but also for other requests on the root route (like `favicon.ico` or `vercel.svg`):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29319414/157678543-bc40385a-e470-415a-86cc-515a2edde22f.png)


---

Is the root middleware expected to work like this?
If yes, shouldn't we add this behavior to the docs?
For example, [the execution order in the docs](https://nextjs.org/docs/middleware#execution-order) only talks about pages, but never about the other requests.


---

# Update with a solution for future readers

You can use `req.page.name` for this purpose. Only page routes will have this filled, all other requests (like external API calls or static assets) will be `undefined`:

```ts
export default async function _middlewareRoot(req: NextRequest) {
  /**
   * The page route.
   * Not the real URL, as the dynamic part/slug (here: `someId`) is "static":
   *
   * `/some-route/abc/[someId]`
   */
  const pageName: string | undefined = req.page.name;
  /**
   * The pathname of the route.
   * The real URL with the real dynamic part/slug (here: `123`):
   *
   * `/some-route/abc/123`
   */
  const pathname = req.nextUrl.pathname;

  /** `pageName` is `undefined` for non-page routes like API calls or static assets */
  const isPageRoute = !!pageName;

  /*
   * This root middleware will also intercept all other requests that are happening in the app (like external API calls
   * or static assets like the favicon) - that's why we here check whether the request was for a page and ignore all other requests.
   * API routes are also considered a page, so they appear as a `pageName` - that's why we exclude them in the following check.
   */
  if (
    !isPageRoute ||
    pageName === ROUTES.SIGN_IN ||
    pageName.startsWith("/api")
  ) {
    // the request is not for one of our pages or it is for the sign in page, or it is an API route request, go on
    return NextResponse.next();
  } else {
    // ... your logic
  }
}

```

