Seeing as Next has to provide these props on the server and rehydrate the static markup on the client, this rich text JSON would be included in the `__NEXT_DATA__` script and we'd regularly get [`large-page-data`](https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/large-page-data) warning from the server logs reporting page data of 150kb+. 

<br>

# Question
Wondering whether anyone has run into a similar situation and how they've handled it? To my mind, there must be a more efficient way of doing this but until now I haven't been able to find one.

As the content is static, and for performance and SEO benefits, I'm keen to use `gSP` to fetch the data at build time and pre-render the HTML for the server. However, I feel that the massive size of the data that has to be included in `__NEXT_DATA__` may actually be having the opposite effect. 

When looking in the .next folder after running a local build, you can see the server-side HTML pages with all the data already there, so does it need to be passed to the client to 'rehydrate' when it shouldn't have changed?

<br>

# One other point
One other thing I have noticed when looking around at other Next sites doing a similar thing is that using markdown seems to yield much better performance. This is most likely down to the much more condensed syntax and the fact that the entire article is sent as a single string.

For example, to generate the following sentence: 

"Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt _consectetur_ adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua."

using JSON rich-text, you would need:

```json
{
  "nodeType": "paragraph",
  "data": {},
  "content": [
    {
      "nodeType": "text",
      "value": "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt",
      "marks": [],
      "data": {}
    },
    { "nodeType": "text", "value": "consectetur ", "marks": [{ "type": "italic" }], "data": {} },
    {
      "nodeType": "text",
      "value": " adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua.",
      "marks": [],
      "data": {}
    }
  ]
}
```

using markdown, you would need:

```json
{
  "data": "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt _consectetur_ adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua."
}
```

With this in mind, I've actually even looked into transforming the Contentful JSON response in markdown and then passing it to the component, but this seems pretty convoluted as once it's received by the component, it's just transformed again using `@contenful/rich-text-react-renderer`, so we're transforming the data twice...

Would love to hear if people are facing the same issue or if anyone has any bright ideas!

