### Describe the feature you'd like to request

Similarly to #9191, which provides a custom validator option for AMP - the native AMP validator provides two additional validators for the following AMP document styles:
- Emails (`AMP4EMAIL`)
- Ads (`AMP4ADS`)

These are already supported by the package - but the code in [`packages/next/export`](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/packages/next/export) will need to be modified to pass an optional parameter to [`validateString`](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/5f033ecb543bdb5d0591db6472cf4c0a346e5c3e/packages/next/export/worker.ts#L438).

This effort seems smaller than #9191, but will need to avoid conflicts between a custom validator and an AMP default. I am assuming if a custom validator is present it'll take precedence over an AMP default.

Future caveat: To fully integrate this feature into the ecosystem, the boilerplate generation for both Ads and Email AMP flavors will likely be needed in the future. Uncertain on the size of this effort - but seems like a win-win situation :)

### Describe the solution you'd like

A configuration setting where the `html_format` flag of `amphtml-validator` can be set to either `ads` or `email` - which map to the corresponding `AMP4ADS` and `AMP4EMAIL` params passed to the `validateString` function - per [documentation](https://amp.dev/documentation/guides-and-tutorials/learn/validation-workflow/validate_emails#usage)

```ts
const nextConfig = {
  amp: { 
     validatorFlavor:  'email', /* or 'ads*/
  },
};

module.exports = nextConfig;
```

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Manually modifying the Next.js output, stripping the non-compliant `head` fields, and running the email/ads validator manually.

### Describe the feature you'd like to request

next/link and router.push and family all do route on the client side. There are cases where you want to render a non-client side link or do a full page load push.

Notably, for pages related to security you often want to flush out any remaining state and start fresh, especially for a log out action.

A simple approach like `window.location.assign('/');` fails when you have a base path and/or locale path involved.

### Describe the solution you'd like

I imagine an API similar to `router.push()`, but instead of having a side effect, it returns the full URL where the resolved path should go to.

An example case using a hypothetical `router.resolve()` for a log out flow looks like this:

```jsx
function Logout() {
  const router = useRouter();
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      onClick={async () => {
        await logout(); // make logout request to server
        window.location.assign(router.resolve('/login')); // navigate to login
        // resolve returning "https://example.com/basepath/en/login"
      }}
    >
      Log out
    </button>
  );
}
```

### Describe alternatives you've considered

I believe a `router.resolve()` function would be the reasonable core functionality, upon which more specialized solutions could be built.

The only existing alternatives are hacks involving rendering next/link and retrieving the href value using a ref, or double loading the destination page by navigating client-side first and then calling `window.location.reload();`.

