### Describe the feature you'd like to request

The [`next/image` `<Image>` component](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/image-optimization) and default loader automatically optimizes images to WebP (and optionally AVIF) using the loader path `/_next/image?url=...`.

When combined with the Cloudflare CDN, the default behaviour is that WebP variants will be cached and served to any clients even if they don't support WebP because Cloudflare does not adhere to the `Vary` header by default. This breaks some older clients like IE11 which obviously do not support WebP.

[One workaround previously documented](https://st4ng.medium.com/how-to-use-next-js-image-optimization-with-cloudflare-569da7b3ddc6) was to add a special transform rule to Cloudflare that appends a `&webp=` parameter to the path for cache-keying purposes.

Since that workaround was published, Cloudflare [actually announced a feature](https://blog.cloudflare.com/vary-for-images-serve-the-correct-images-to-the-correct-browsers/) called [Vary for Images](https://developers.cloudflare.com/cache/about/vary-for-images/) for this specific scenario of using the `Vary` and `Accept` header to dynamically serve and caching different versions of an image.

However one limitation of Vary for Images is that it requires the URL path must include an [image extension](https://developers.cloudflare.com/cache/about/vary-for-images/#file-extensions) from their list of supported image extensions
```
.avif
.bmp
.gif
.jpg
.jpeg
.jp2
.png
.tif
.tiff
.webp
```

